N2  - The Eighties witnessed a reversal in the gradual decline of poverty which had taken place in Latin America since 1950. This paper discusses the factors behind such reversal and the macroeconomic, institutional and targeted policies needed for significant poverty over the medium term. In the past, poverty was mainly a rural phenomenon rooted in inequitable agrarian structures, limited access to education and a marked urban bias. In the Eighties, in contrast, while declining slightly in the country side, poverty rose significantly in cities, thus becoming mainly an urban phenomenon. This surge in poverty resulted from the interaction among a severe recession, contractionary adjustment policies and a permanent increase in inequality due to greater wealth concentration, erosion of the State's redistributive role and radical labor market changes. Poverty reduction will thus require not only a broadbased recovery and targeted social interventions but also institutional reforms involving labor and fiscal policies and land distribution.
